<P>
 THE PIANO TUNER by Peter Meinke (University of Georgia Press: $11.95; 156 pp.) 
. Meinke's short stories depict people caught in alarming situations: Their 
inability to cope with anything outside normal experience reveals the decay of 
American society. In "Alice's Brother," a woman unnerved by her sibling's 
surgery delivers a desperate monologue reminiscent of a Dorothy Parker story; 
"Sealink" opens with the wonderfully incongruous line, "Emily had never hit a 
sheep before." Like Hans Christian Andersen's Emperor, Meinke's people stand 
exposed before the world, struggling to hide their vulnerability. 
