<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'LIFE WITH MIKEY' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Peter Rainer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The main reason to see this 1993 release is for Michael J. Fox's all-out 
performance as a former child TV star who peaked at 15 and now runs a 
third-rate kids' talent agency. As Michael Chapman, Fox (right) has the haggard 
look of an actor who played out his childhood on television without ever having 
played it out in his own life.By doggedly running the talent agency with his 
brother (Nathan Lane) and their gum-popping secretary (Cyndi Lauper), Michael 
is, in a sense, trying to replay his childhood all over again -- but this time 
from the driver's seat. The film isn't as syrupy as it might be, mostly due to 
a 10-year-old (Christina Vidal, left) who shows up as the answer to the 
agency's dreams; she plays it spunky rather than twinkly (Showtime Monday at 
noon and 8 p.m.; Saturday at 4:45 p.m.). Peter Rainer 
</P>
</TEXT>
