<HEADLINE>
<P>
EVERYBODY'S TALKING; WHAT A 'WILD' COUPLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Chuck Crisafulli 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When musicians of contrasting sensibilities team up in the studio, it's 
anyone's guess whether the results will sizzle or fizzle. 
</P>
<P>
 Heartland rocker John Mellencamp may have been taking a gamble when he asked 
funk artist Me'shell NdegeOcello to play and sing with him on a version of Van 
Morrison's "Wild Night," but he's delighted with the results. The single, which 
was released May 9, also appears on Mellencamp's new "Dance Naked" album and is 
currently in the Top 10 on the national pop chart. 
</P>
<P>
 Mellencamp got the idea for the surprise teaming after hearing NdegeOcello's 
acclaimed debut album, "Plantation Lullabies," which was released last year by 
Madonna's Maverick Records. 
</P>
<P>
 "I liked what she did," Mellencamp explains. "I thought she was the real 
item." 
</P>
<P>
 NdegeOcello, whose "If That Was Your Boyfriend (He Wasn't Last Night)" is 
another of the most-talked-about singles of 1994, turned out to be a big 
Mellencamp fan and agreed to team up with him. 
</P>
<P>
 The original idea was for her to just add some powerful bass licks to "Wild 
Night" and one other album track, "The Big Jack." But Mellencamp decided he 
wanted a second voice on "Wild Night," which he had been doing off and on in 
concert for years. Since his longtime backup vocalist and fiddle player Lisa 
Germano wasn't at the session, NdegeOcello was called into service. The pairing 
clicked and the song was completed in two takes. 
</P>
<P>
 NdegeOcello, who performed "Wild Night" with Mellencamp at the MTV Movie 
Awards in June, has a standing invitation to join him on stage when her 
schedule coincides with his tour (which includes Sept. 13 and 14 shows at the 
Greek Theatre and a Sept. 16 date at the Glen Helen Blockbuster Pavilion). She 
planned to do so during a recent show at Tipitina's in New Orleans, but was 
sidelined by a strep throat.* 
</P>
</TEXT>
