<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; POLICE DEPARTMENT ANNOUNCES PROMOTIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MACK REED 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Four Simi Valley police officers have been promoted effective Sept. 5, the 
date when nearly 25% of the department's 109 sworn officers are expected to 
change assignments in a departmentwide shake-up, Chief Willard R. Schlieter 
said.  
</P>
<P>
 Schlieter said last week that he has promoted Sgts.Kenneth Tacke and Rex Jones 
to the rank of lieutenant. 
</P>
<P>
 Tacke, 42, is a 19-year veteran of the department working most recently in the 
detective division supervising property crime and violent crime investigations. 
Jones, 39, has been a Simi Valley officer for more than 17 years and was 
working in the support services division on training and internal affairs. 
</P>
<P>
 Schlieter also promoted Officers Anthony Anzilotti and Gregory Riegert to the 
rank of sergeant. 
</P>
<P>
 Anzilotti, 31, has served 10 years with the department in assignments ranging 
from patrol and training to the detectives division and the Special Weapons 
Team. 
</P>
<P>
 Riegert, 37, has worked in the Simi Valley department for 15 years, serving at 
times in the patrol, traffic and detectives divisions as well as administration 
and the Special Enforcement Detail. 
</P>
<P>
 Schlieter said the four men's promotions created vacancies that other officers 
will be shuffled to fill. He also plans to reassign the department's 
lieutenants to new duties, something he promised to do soon after taking office 
in March. 
</P>
<P>
 "I asked for volunteers for each of those assignments, and from those I did 
make some new assignments," he said. "It's really something (the lieutenants) 
are eager to have happen." 
</P>
<P>
 Schlieter said that by the time all the changes are finished, about 25 to 30 
officers will have switched duties. MACK REED 
</P>
</TEXT>
